  "prompt": "How long can a human being survive without sleep?",
  "response": "The longest documented case of a human staying awake is about 11 days (264 hours), achieved by Randy Gardner in 1964 during a high school science experiment. However, prolonged sleep deprivation can have severe health consequences:\n\n1. After 24 hours: Cognitive impairment similar to being legally drunk\n2. After 36 hours: Increased inflammation, weakened immune system\n3. After 48 hours: Microsleeps, hallucinations, mood changes\n4. After 72 hours: Severe cognitive decline, potential psychological effects\n\nWhile someone might technically survive without sleep for about 11 days, it's extremely dangerous and can cause serious physical and mental health problems. Most humans cannot function properly after just a few days without sleep. Experts recommend 7-9 hours of sleep per night for optimal health.\n\nProlonged sleep deprivation can ultimately lead to death, though this is typically due to the cascading health effects rather than sleep loss itself. The exact point at which sleep deprivation becomes fatal varies by individual.",
